WEBVTT

00:00.452 --> 00:02.208
Previously on Ugly Betty...

00:02.218 --> 00:03.533
Killer poncho.

00:03.543 --> 00:04.911
Thanks!

00:05.026 --> 00:07.094
- I'm Betty Suarez.
- Hi, Betty.

00:07.114 --> 00:08.848
I'm your new assistant.

00:08.993 --> 00:11.527
I got the job because Bradford
Meade didn't want his son

00:11.537 --> 00:13.411
to be tempted to sleep
with his assistant.

00:13.421 --> 00:16.181
Nepotistic son of a bitch
gives my job to his...

00:16.192 --> 00:17.608
His son.

00:17.865 --> 00:21.172
So the question is,
how do we get to Bradford?

00:21.180 --> 00:22.914
We use Daniel.

00:22.927 --> 00:24.196
Who is this?

00:24.206 --> 00:27.036
He's a man of many,
many secrets, Daniel.

00:27.048 --> 00:28.331
Dig a little deeper,

00:28.348 --> 00:31.940
and you may find he's capable
of practically anything.

00:34.036 --> 00:35.490
Excuse me, sir.

00:35.508 --> 00:37.793
You know,
I think I was here before them.

00:40.377 --> 00:42.613
This is a party for my boss.

00:42.625 --> 00:44.961
Daniel Meade--
I'm his assistant.

00:46.025 --> 00:50.043
No, I am, I am. Here, look,
I have--I have my xerox card.

00:50.056 --> 00:51.992
It's here somewhere.
I know I have it.

00:52.005 --> 00:54.290
They don't just give
these to anybody.

00:54.305 --> 00:56.293
Oh, see, she knows me. Amanda!

00:56.305 --> 00:58.173
- Right this way.
- Amanda!

00:59.116 --> 01:01.390
Sweetheart, why don't you
come back on monday night?

01:01.407 --> 01:03.572
That's when we let anybody in.

01:08.057 --> 01:11.511
Oh! Here, look, I found it.
My--my xerox card.

01:11.527 --> 01:15.460
I'm standing outside Vamp,
Manhattan's hot spot de jour,

01:15.475 --> 01:19.213
and it's nothing but trendy and fendi
here for Daniel Meade's cover party,

01:19.226 --> 01:23.390
as we celebrate his first issue
of "Mode" hitting the stands.

01:23.406 --> 01:26.151
More than a few eyebrows
were raised on the catwalk

01:26.168 --> 01:29.430
when Meade was chosen to
replace the late Fey Sommers

01:29.447 --> 01:32.882
over seasoned creative
director Wilhelmina Slater.

01:32.895 --> 01:36.711
Miss Slater, this way!
Wilhelmina, hi! You're gorgeous!

01:37.387 --> 01:38.301
What'd I miss?

01:38.316 --> 01:41.210
"The Times," "Page Six," "The News"--
they've been all over Daniel.

01:41.226 --> 01:43.900
Heidi Klum is a no-show,
Isaac's in the back getting sloppy,

01:43.915 --> 01:47.222
oh, and... wait till you see
Veronica Jensen's face-lift.

01:47.237 --> 01:48.890
Lawsuit!

01:49.747 --> 01:53.212
Look at them, falling all over
themselves trying to get a quote.

01:53.225 --> 01:55.610
As if he actually knew
anything about fashion.

01:55.628 --> 01:58.733
The man went to Vera Wang's spring line,
gave her a high-five.

01:59.108 --> 02:02.021
# But I can't seem to #
# get you over here #

02:02.035 --> 02:05.563
# To help take this off, #
# baby can't you see #

02:05.577 --> 02:08.332
# How these clothes
are fitting on me? #

02:09.608 --> 02:13.073
# Dance! #
# Dance dance revolution #

02:13.088 --> 02:15.833
# Keep ya body movin' #

02:19.105 --> 02:21.272
# Now first things first... #

02:25.005 --> 02:25.753
Hi.

02:25.768 --> 02:27.851
Walter, what are
you doing here?

02:27.868 --> 02:29.552
Okay, my turn.

02:29.567 --> 02:31.271
Betty, check it out.

02:32.786 --> 02:35.592
Actually, I think, uh,

02:35.605 --> 02:38.061
I'm the one that should be
asking the questions here.

02:38.077 --> 02:42.151
Like, what were you doing out at
some club with your boss till...

02:42.245 --> 02:44.241
9:45?

02:44.255 --> 02:46.711
Well, it was a party
for his first issue.

02:46.728 --> 02:48.813
And why am I explaining
this to you, Walter?

02:48.825 --> 02:50.413
We're not even dating anymore.

02:50.428 --> 02:51.950
Yeah, and whose fault is that?

02:51.966 --> 02:54.651
Well, you're the one
who dumped me for Gina.

02:54.668 --> 02:56.272
For just two days,

02:56.287 --> 02:58.990
and it takes longer than
that to digest corn.

02:59.005 --> 03:02.321
As beautiful an apology as that is,
Walter, I think we're over.

03:02.335 --> 03:03.963
Come on.

03:03.975 --> 03:05.991
Betty, look what I brought you.

03:06.005 --> 03:08.231
This game's been on
back-order for two months.

03:08.246 --> 03:10.470
Couldn't even use my discount.
Full price.

03:10.485 --> 03:11.923
So I'm supposed to
forgive you because

03:11.955 --> 03:14.601
you couldn't use your
employee discount?

03:14.618 --> 03:17.371
Walter, go home.

03:17.385 --> 03:20.031
I would,
but we're in the middle of a game here.

03:20.047 --> 03:21.550
Yes!

03:21.566 --> 03:23.242
Okay...

03:23.255 --> 03:25.270
now I'm gonna go home.

03:27.000 --> 03:33.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:36.016 --> 03:38.170
Full price!

03:46.865 --> 03:50.712
July issue. Black lace push-up bra, 
red mesh thong.

03:50.725 --> 03:52.072
See, I never forget a face.

03:52.087 --> 03:55.441
Careful, Daniel,
I think she's only 12.

03:55.697 --> 03:57.410
Hi, dad.

03:58.665 --> 04:00.983
I see that you've
been mingling.

04:00.997 --> 04:03.351
Are you talking to anyone
who actually matters?

04:03.365 --> 04:05.911
I've done 40
interviews already.

04:05.925 --> 04:08.241
Look's like my first
issue's a home run, huh?

04:08.257 --> 04:10.161
Yeah, you pulled it off.

04:10.175 --> 04:12.251
Christy Benson from "New
York Minute" seems to think

04:12.258 --> 04:14.380
I did a little more
than pull it off.

04:14.395 --> 04:15.900
You're the editor
of "Mode," Daniel.

04:15.916 --> 04:17.310
"Mode" sells "Mode."

04:17.325 --> 04:20.003
Mr. Meade,
can we get a 2-shot with Daniel?

04:20.368 --> 04:23.340
A couple more, sir?
This way. Thank you.

04:27.108 --> 04:29.132
Well, if that wasn't
a cover shot--

04:29.148 --> 04:33.243
media mogul Bradford Meade and his son,
the shining star.

04:33.255 --> 04:34.840
The issue's a big hit, Daniel,

04:34.855 --> 04:36.953
and your brother really
would've been proud.

04:36.966 --> 04:38.483
Well, I'm not so
sure about that.

04:38.495 --> 04:40.140
What did I do, anyway?

04:40.157 --> 04:42.741
"Mode" sells
"Mode." Right, dad?

04:42.835 --> 04:44.820
You remember the yacht?

04:44.848 --> 04:46.841
Your dad throws this
party to introduce Alex

04:46.856 --> 04:48.512
to the entire fashion community

04:48.527 --> 04:49.942
as the new editor of "Hudson."

04:49.955 --> 04:52.483
He walks in with a black
pinstripe Armani jacket,

04:52.495 --> 04:54.291
white  tuxedo front shirt

04:54.307 --> 04:57.041
and polka-dot boxers.

04:58.085 --> 05:01.152
That  picture ended up in almost
every newspaper in the country.

05:01.167 --> 05:03.643
Circulation went up 38%.

05:03.658 --> 05:05.060
That is an editor.

05:05.075 --> 05:06.140
Well, you should've
told me that, dad.

05:06.178 --> 05:08.722
I would've gladly
dropped my pants for you.

05:10.295 --> 05:12.700
Oh, sorry.

05:12.716 --> 05:15.621
Maybe it was insensitive of
me to mention him tonight?

05:15.637 --> 05:19.442
This is Daniel's party,
but, uh, Alex is such a...

05:19.456 --> 05:21.530
tough act to follow.

05:22.376 --> 05:25.411
So was the club amazing?

05:25.426 --> 05:28.661
They say people wait in line for,
like, three hours just to get inside.

05:28.678 --> 05:29.971
Some even more.

05:29.985 --> 05:31.460
You're home early.

05:31.478 --> 05:32.852
I checked your homework.

05:32.866 --> 05:34.191
Was there any famous
people there?

05:34.228 --> 05:35.731
Did you bring me a matchbook?

05:35.747 --> 05:37.010
Justin, I forgot.

05:37.028 --> 05:39.962
Well, what about the bathroom doors? Do
they really fog over when you push a button?

05:39.996 --> 05:42.111
Justin,  I...
didn't have to use the bathroom.

05:42.128 --> 05:44.700
Okay, Justin,
go get ready for bed.

05:45.477 --> 05:48.990
And by the way,
I read your boss' first issue.

05:49.006 --> 05:54.170
A little bulky, but good balance of
style, accessories and puff pieces.

05:56.627 --> 05:58.851
You didn't get in, did you?

05:59.857 --> 06:02.523
I have to go e-mail Daniel
his itinerary for tomorrow.

06:02.536 --> 06:04.052
Síentate.

06:04.347 --> 06:06.651
Why do you do this
to yourself, hmm?

06:06.665 --> 06:09.342
I keep telling you,
those places aren't for people like us.

06:09.357 --> 06:13.111
Hilda, please, just... don't.

06:15.448 --> 06:17.030
Okay.

06:17.046 --> 06:21.593
Okay, look, if this is so
important to you, let me help you.

06:21.606 --> 06:23.133
- How?
- How?!

06:23.148 --> 06:26.553
I am the top-selling Herbalux
sale associate in my district,

06:26.565 --> 06:29.701
and all because I know
how to sell myself--

06:29.718 --> 06:31.982
the hair, the face,
the clothes.

06:31.998 --> 06:34.621
You gotta look it to be it.
That's the Herbalux way.

06:34.635 --> 06:37.731
Thanks, but I don't think so.

06:38.826 --> 06:41.632
Betty, mama...

06:41.647 --> 06:43.692
you wanna fit in
with these people?

06:43.700 --> 06:45.484
I got news for you--

06:46.357 --> 06:48.156
they're not gonna change.

06:48.166 --> 06:51.056
Mnh-mnh. You have to.

06:51.878 --> 06:54.042
I'm gonna get chocolate sauce.

07:33.047 --> 07:34.500
Hey.

07:34.626 --> 07:36.230
Good morning to you, too.

07:36.245 --> 07:37.883
You know what the doctor said.

07:37.895 --> 07:39.703
You already threw
away my cigars.

07:39.716 --> 07:41.440
- One lousy cup of coffee--
- Oh, I'm sorry.

07:41.456 --> 07:43.520
Have you been going to medical
school on your lunch hour?

07:43.555 --> 07:46.562
Dad, you have to take this more
seriously. This is your heart.

07:46.577 --> 07:48.563
- Have you taken your pill?
- I only have a few left.

07:48.596 --> 07:50.963
- I'm trying to make 'em last.
- Dad, take it.

07:50.976 --> 07:52.143
We'll get a refill.

07:52.158 --> 07:54.463
All right, I'm taking it,
I'm taking it.

07:54.476 --> 07:57.620
You know, I actually think I'm making
some headway on this H.M.O. thing.

07:57.638 --> 08:00.052
I finally got a real person
on the phone yesterday

08:00.066 --> 08:02.861
instead of some
stupid recording.

08:04.287 --> 08:07.151
I had to wash it
down with something.

08:22.078 --> 08:24.112
You didn't stay
long last night.

08:24.128 --> 08:25.632
No, sorry.

08:25.645 --> 08:28.101
I had to wake up early for
the conference call to Milan,

08:28.118 --> 08:30.800
and then go over 
the kiera shoot proofs, and then

08:30.816 --> 08:33.191
approve the models
for the Paris spread.

08:33.205 --> 08:34.701
It's 9:15.

08:34.715 --> 08:38.652
Well, someone's got to hold this
magazine together, Bradford.

08:38.664 --> 08:41.393
I mean, Daniel is trying,

08:41.407 --> 08:45.040
but, uh,
some people are just naturals.

08:45.058 --> 08:46.480
Don't worry.

08:46.495 --> 08:48.571
I've got his back.

09:00.925 --> 09:03.623
Excuse me. I'm sorry.

09:03.638 --> 09:06.101
Well, don't you look... sweaty?

09:06.116 --> 09:09.513
I've been in the archives.
Daniel wanted all these back issues.

09:09.537 --> 09:12.732
Mm-hmm. Well, we missed you 
at the party last night.

09:12.747 --> 09:16.533
What happened,
sale at the 99 cents store?

09:17.167 --> 09:19.802
No, I... I couldn't get in.

09:19.815 --> 09:23.033
Are you serious?
Oh, you poor thing.

09:23.047 --> 09:24.672
Those jerks at the door...

09:24.685 --> 09:28.421
all they seem to care
about is appearance.

09:29.958 --> 09:33.442
Look, it's all about appearance.
That's all Alex did to "Hudson."

09:33.455 --> 09:36.860
He changed the font, the layout,
hired some trendy photographers,

09:36.878 --> 09:39.231
and my father thinks
he's some kind of hero.

09:39.247 --> 09:41.272
I can do these same
things to "Mode."

09:41.287 --> 09:43.810
But, Daniel,
your first issue was a big success.

09:43.827 --> 09:45.732
My nephew loved it.

09:45.748 --> 09:47.731
It wasn't my issue,
and you know it.

09:47.748 --> 09:50.523
I mean, Wilhelmina chose every designer,
every article.

09:50.537 --> 09:54.063
I just signed my initials
to lots of memos. I...

09:55.865 --> 09:57.631
That's gonna change.

09:58.745 --> 10:01.112
Set up a staff
meeting for monday--

10:01.126 --> 10:02.511
all department heads,

10:02.528 --> 10:04.300
and work around my
father's schedule.

10:04.318 --> 10:06.452
I want him there, too.

10:07.426 --> 10:10.320
Two words-- fa boo.

10:10.338 --> 10:12.693
It's for that breast
cancer thing at the plaza.

10:12.707 --> 10:15.391
And who's the lucky "plus one"?

10:15.406 --> 10:17.022
The senator's in town.

10:17.038 --> 10:18.910
I thought breast
cancer was pink.

10:18.925 --> 10:22.353
It is, but alzheimer's went
better with the outfit.

10:22.387 --> 10:25.712
What? I'm supporting.
That's what counts.

10:25.728 --> 10:27.102
Zip me.

10:27.117 --> 10:28.742
What do you want, anyhow?

10:28.755 --> 10:30.082
Conference room,

10:30.095 --> 10:31.811
and it's good.

10:31.828 --> 10:34.323
So here are all the models
that Alex worked with,

10:34.336 --> 10:37.233
and I found that font
style that he used.

10:37.245 --> 10:40.533
Um, also, I brought all of
these photographers' books.

10:40.548 --> 10:43.190
This one right here--this is
my favorite. He's amazing.

10:43.208 --> 10:46.180
He's shot everyone from, like,
Madonna to the Dalai Lama.

10:46.197 --> 10:48.202
Yeah, this is
Vincent Bianchi...

10:48.216 --> 10:50.263
and he'll never work for us.

10:50.278 --> 10:51.250
Well, why not?

10:51.268 --> 10:53.640
When he worked with Alex,
they got in this huge blowup.

10:53.658 --> 10:55.120
He thought Alex was a fraud.

10:55.135 --> 10:57.342
Alex thought he was some
temperamental artiste.

10:57.357 --> 11:00.591
He vowed never to work for
Meade Publications again.

11:00.607 --> 11:02.243
But, Daniel, you're not Alex.

11:02.257 --> 11:04.412
Look, if my brother the
wunderkind couldn't make it work,

11:04.446 --> 11:06.842
I seriously doubt
I'd be able to...

11:06.856 --> 11:11.340
Look, let's just, uh,
see who else is here, huh?

11:13.117 --> 11:15.563
Tweedledee and Tweedledumpy have
been in there for two hours

11:15.576 --> 11:18.091
going over back
issues of "Hudson."

11:18.107 --> 11:22.473
Now... he's trying to actually
rip off his own dead brother.

11:22.486 --> 11:26.262
Oh, my god, it couldn't be any
easier if I gave him the gun,

11:26.277 --> 11:28.733
and he aimed it at his foot.

11:35.088 --> 11:39.550
The police released Fey Sommers' car
to a scrape metal yard a week ago.

11:39.567 --> 11:42.313
How come it's taking you so
long to find out where it is?

11:42.328 --> 11:44.041
Location info is private,

11:44.058 --> 11:48.071
and there's over 142 salvage
yards in the Tristate area alone.

11:48.088 --> 11:50.691
Why don't you just go back to your
big building and make magazines,

11:50.728 --> 11:52.080
and  let me do what I do?

11:52.095 --> 11:54.763
Well, you better do
what you do quickly.

11:54.775 --> 11:57.663
The grease monkeys in these garages
can't spell their own names,

11:57.678 --> 11:59.422
but it won't take much
for them to figure out

11:59.455 --> 12:02.051
the steering was tampered with.

12:02.165 --> 12:05.583
And I don't care how good
you think your work is.

12:12.107 --> 12:14.883
What are we drinking to?

12:14.897 --> 12:17.031
To a father who
realizes his child

12:17.046 --> 12:19.120
will never compare
to the one he lost

12:19.137 --> 12:22.240
and to a son who knows
he'll never measure up,

12:22.256 --> 12:24.583
no matter how hard he tries.

12:24.996 --> 12:28.372
It's practically shakespearean.

12:28.385 --> 12:31.272
As long as there's this wedge
between the two of them,

12:31.285 --> 12:33.450
their relationship is doomed.

12:33.467 --> 12:36.931
Daniel's time at the magazine--
and ultimately, the company--

12:36.947 --> 12:38.363
will be limited.

12:38.375 --> 12:44.003
Well, perhaps it's time I drive
that wedge a little deeper.

12:44.015 --> 12:46.872
What would Daniel think
if he were tipped off

12:46.885 --> 12:50.883
as to what his dear old
father were capable of?

13:00.198 --> 13:02.362
Hey, what if we shrink
the magazine down

13:02.376 --> 13:06.013
so women can fit it in
their purses easier?

13:12.457 --> 13:14.873
See, now Alex
would've made that.

13:15.357 --> 13:17.873
He should be the one here doing this,
not me.

13:17.885 --> 13:19.523
At least my father
would be happier.

13:19.538 --> 13:21.503
If your father didn't think
you could do this job,

13:21.538 --> 13:23.923
then why would he
give it to you?

13:25.056 --> 13:29.453
Is this...
kung pao chicken or--or orange beef?

13:29.468 --> 13:33.770
Well, after five hours, Daniel,
I-I don't really think it matters.

13:35.147 --> 13:36.930
You know what next saturday is?

13:36.947 --> 13:39.923
The Harvard/Yale game. Biggest 
college football game of the year.

13:39.938 --> 13:41.923
You want me to try
and get you tickets?

13:41.936 --> 13:43.000
You know,
every year since we were kids,

13:43.038 --> 13:46.492
my father would take Alex to that game.
It was their--their thing.

13:46.517 --> 13:49.293
He never once invited me.

13:52.687 --> 13:55.690
You know,
I actually thought after Alex died,

13:55.705 --> 13:58.312
he was gonna ask
me to go, but...

14:00.685 --> 14:02.811
It's okay. I'm used to it.

14:02.828 --> 14:05.552
Every parent has
a favorite, right?

14:06.496 --> 14:08.590
Well, you know, my dad doesn't.

14:08.605 --> 14:11.221
Sure, he does.
I mean, they all do.

14:11.235 --> 14:15.453
Sometimes it's, uh, something small,
but you can see it, you know?

14:15.466 --> 14:20.462
They, uh, smile a little brighter
when one of you walks in the room...

14:20.475 --> 14:25.183
laugh  a little louder when
one of you tells a joke.

14:37.148 --> 14:38.490
Good morning!

14:38.505 --> 14:40.763
Justin, you are not
gonna make me late today!

14:40.776 --> 14:42.302
What time did you
get in last night?

14:42.317 --> 14:43.891
I don't even remember.

14:43.905 --> 14:46.141
Daniel's going through a bunch
of stuff with his father...

14:46.175 --> 14:47.462
Justin!

14:51.998 --> 14:53.530
What?

14:54.527 --> 14:58.601
Hilda, do you ever think about

14:58.617 --> 15:00.953
dad and us and,

15:00.967 --> 15:03.233
you know, if he has a favorite?

15:03.248 --> 15:04.772
Yeah, I think so.

15:04.787 --> 15:06.953
- You.
- You.

15:06.966 --> 15:09.281
Come on, you're right up
there between Tito Puente

15:09.295 --> 15:11.583
and his nose hair clippers.

15:11.618 --> 15:14.312
I am gonna kill that kid.
Morning, papi.

15:14.327 --> 15:16.320
You didn't get in
till 3:00 last night.

15:16.337 --> 15:17.840
Why they keeping so late?

15:17.856 --> 15:20.110
Well, my boss is trying to make
some changes at the magazine,

15:20.147 --> 15:22.641
and I still have to go through
these photographers' books.

15:22.656 --> 15:24.510
Well, they're
working you too hard.

15:24.528 --> 15:26.163
You tell 'em you want a raise.

15:26.177 --> 15:27.451
Okay, dad.

15:27.466 --> 15:29.050
Vincent Bianchi?

15:29.065 --> 15:30.950
Yeah, he's really amazing.

15:30.966 --> 15:33.102
So he ended up making it
as a photographer, huh?

15:33.118 --> 15:35.053
Damn, I always thought that
kid would end up in jail.

15:35.085 --> 15:36.412
What are you talking about?

15:36.425 --> 15:38.881
Vinnie Bianchi--
he grew up over on Grand.

15:38.896 --> 15:41.110
His family owns
Astoria Lemon Ice.

15:41.127 --> 15:42.851
He grew up four
blocks from here?!

15:42.868 --> 15:46.180
Yeah, his old man's always going
on about his kid's pictures.

15:46.195 --> 15:48.771
He's got a bunch of 'em hanging
up on the wall in there.

15:48.786 --> 15:50.870
